diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with a wide range of symptoms, including acute pericarditis, fever, proteinuria (due to lupus nephritis), psychosis, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Viral Pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Viral infections are a common cause of acute pericarditis and can also lead to fever and pericardial effusion. Psychosis might not be directly related but could occur as a severe systemic reaction in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.rationale: Rheumatic fever follows a Streptococcus pyogenes infection and may cause fever, acute pericarditis, and pericardial effusion. Other symptoms like arthritis are more common than proteinuria and psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD combines features of several diseases like SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis and can present with acute pericarditis, fever, proteinuria, and occasionally neuropsychiatric symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Drug-Induced Lupus
diagnoses.rationale: Certain drugs can induce lupus-like symptoms, including acute pericarditis, fever, and pericardial effusion. Psychosis is less common but not unheard of. Drug-induced lupus rarely causes kidney involvement, hence proteinuria might suggest another cause.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.rationale: Although scleroderma typically affects the skin, it can also involve internal organs and present with pericardial effusion and acute pericarditis. Renal crisis can lead to proteinuria. Neurologic manifestations including psychosis are rare.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis (Pericardial Tuberculosis)
diagnoses.rationale: Tuberculosis can cause pericardial effusion and acute pericarditis. Fever is common due to the infection, and in severe cases, disseminated TB can affect the kidneys (leading to proteinuria) and potentially the brain (possibly contributing to psychosis).

diagnoses.name: Post-viral Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Following a viral infection, some patients develop a prolonged syndrome that can include pericardial effusion, fever, and less commonly, psychiatric symptoms. Proteinuria might occur due to transient renal impairment.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV can lead to a wide array of symptoms and opportunistic infections that could explain this symptom complex, including acute pericarditis, fever, proteinuria (from HIV-associated nephropathy), and neurological symptoms including psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily affecting the heart's valves, endocarditis can lead to fever and, in severe cases, affect various organs leading to proteinuria. Acute pericarditis is less common but can occur. Pericardial effusion and psychosis are possible but rare complications.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder causing the body to absorb too much iron from the diet. The excess iron is stored in various organs, particularly the liver. Hyperferritinemia is a common finding in hemochromatosis.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that leads to abnormal blood vessel formation and frequent bleeding episodes, including epistaxis (nosebleeds).

diagnoses.name: Von Willebrand Disease
diagnoses.description: A bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency of von Willebrand factor, which helps blood to clot. This can lead to easy bleeding and is often associated with episodes of epistaxis.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal increase in white blood cells. It can cause hyperferritinemia, easy bleeding, and non-specific symptoms such as fatigue, which could contribute to depressive symptoms and non-restorative sleep.

diagnoses.name: Liver disease
diagnoses.description: Conditions affecting the liver that can lead to hyperferritinemia due to iron overload, and also impair clotting, resulting in easy bleeding. Non-restorative sleep and depression can be associated with chronic liver disease.

diagnoses.name: Chronic inflammation
diagnoses.description: Chronic inflammatory processes can lead to hyperferritinemia as ferritin is an acute-phase reactant. These conditions may also affect sleep and mood, contributing to symptoms of depression.

diagnoses.name: Myelodysplastic syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders caused by poorly formed or dysfunctional blood cells. Patients may present with hyperferritinemia due to iron overload from frequent blood transfusions, easy bleeding, and systemic symptoms that could include mood changes.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety disorder
diagnoses.description: While primarily a psychiatric condition, severe anxiety can exacerbate or mimic the perception of physical health issues, including non-restorative sleep, fatigue, and potential psychosomatic manifestations of bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Iron overload syndromes other than hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: These can include conditions such as transfusion-related iron overload or secondary hemochromatosis due to chronic liver disease, leading to hyperferritinemia and associated symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Thrombocytopenia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by low platelet counts leading to easy bleeding and possibly contributing to epistaxis. It can be secondary to a variety of conditions, including leukemia and systemic diseases, which may also cause hyperferritinemia and depressive symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that starts in certain blood-forming cells of the bone marrow. It can lead to increased levels of white blood cells (leukocytosis) and basophils (basophilia), which may affect the body's ability to fight infections.

diagnoses.name: Myeloproliferative Neoplasms
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that involve overproduction of blood cells in the bone marrow. These conditions can cause basophilia and leukocytosis, and may indirectly lead to an increased susceptibility to infections and other complications.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing malabsorption and potentially leading to miscarriages due to malnutrition and the body's inability to absorb key nutrients.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease
diagnoses.description: A term for two conditions (Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis) that are characterized by chronic inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, leading to malabsorption and potentially affecting pregnancy outcomes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the joints, skin, kidneys, heart, lungs, blood vessels, and brain. It can cause leukocytosis and is associated with a higher risk of miscarriage.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection and acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) lead to a weakened immune system, thereby increasing susceptibility to infections. The virus can also affect the body's ability to manage other conditions, potentially impacting pregnancy outcomes.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Diseases
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders caused by defects in the body's immune system, leading to an increased susceptibility to infections. These conditions can indirectly lead to complications related to malabsorption and may impact pregnancy.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, which primarily affects the lungs but can affect other parts of the body. It can lead to an increased susceptibility to infections and has been associated with adverse pregnancy outcomes.

diagnoses.name: Sickle Cell Disease
diagnoses.description: A group of inherited red blood cell disorders. It's known to cause an increased susceptibility to infections and may have indirect effects on pregnancy outcomes due to its complications like anemia and malabsorption of nutrients.

diagnoses.name: Whipple's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare bacterial infection that can lead to malabsorption due to thickening of the intestinal wall. This condition can affect various systems and may contribute to a broad range of symptoms including those affecting pregnancy outcomes.
A skin condition characterized by small blisters on the hands or feet, often associated with itching and flaking skin.
A pathological wound healing in which connective tissue replaces normal parenchymal tissue to the extent that it interferes with organ function; can be caused by many types of chronic damage.
A condition that affects circulation (blood flow) resulting in symptoms like lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat that occur upon standing.
A common disorder that affects the large intestine, causing symptoms like bloating, gas, constipation, and diarrhea.
An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing symptoms like bloating, diarrhea, and weight loss.
An allergic/immune condition where a type of white blood cell (eosinophil) builds up in the esophagus, causing symptoms like dysphagia (difficulty swallowing) and heartburn.

A condition in which mast cells inappropriately release chemical mediators, leading to a wide range of chronic symptoms including dermatological issues, gastrointestinal distress, and cardiovascular symptoms.

A group of diseases that result in high blood sugar (glucose), either due to insulin production issues or the body's inability to use insulin effectively, leading to hypoglycemia management challenges.

An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands responsible for keeping the eyes, mouth, and other parts of the body moist and lubricated, sometimes associated with other immune system disorders like rheumatoid arthritis.

A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues, potentially linked to a variety of symptoms including those connected to POTS.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Increased susceptibility to infection, periodontal disease, and hyperglycemia are classic signs of poorly controlled diabetes mellitus.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.reasoning: Plethora is a common symptom of polycythemia vera, a type of blood cancer that can increase blood viscosity, leading to various complications including hyperglycemia.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Xerosis (dry skin) and an increased susceptibility to infection could be signs of Sjögren's syndrome, an autoimmune disease that affects the body's moisture-producing glands.

diagnoses.name: Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS)
diagnoses.reasoning: Increased susceptibility to infection may suggest an advanced HIV infection, or AIDS, possibly accompanied by periodontal disease due to immunosuppression.

diagnoses.name: Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Hyperglycemia and increased susceptibility to infection are key indicators of Type 2 diabetes, along with other complications like periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: This rare, inherited disorder affects the immune system, leading to increased susceptibility to infections and possibly affecting skin hydration, manifesting as xerosis.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Though not directly causing hyperglycemia, hypothyroidism can lead to a decreased metabolic rate, which may predispose individuals to diabetes; it also can cause xerosis.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Diseases
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized by increased susceptibility to infections; some types can also lead to dental and skin conditions.

diagnoses.name: Langerhans Cell Histiocytosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This rare disease can lead to a variety of symptoms depending on the organs affected, including skin (xerosis), increased risk of diabetes insipidus (and secondary hyperglycemia), and immune system dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain forms of leukemia can cause increased susceptibility to infection due to immunosuppression, skin conditions, and indirectly affect blood sugar levels.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Hyperglycemia and weight loss are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause lymphadenitis, and potentially lead to transient hyperglycemia.

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.reasoning: Presents with lymphadenitis and weight loss; less commonly affects glucose regulation.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause lymphadenitis, weight loss. Some types might affect glucose metabolism.

diagnoses.name: Addison's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause weight loss, hyperglycemia. Blood pressure lability is also a feature due to adrenal insufficiency.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders (Hyperthyroidism)
diagnoses.reasoning: Weight loss and hyperglycemia might occur, along with blood pressure changes.

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.reasoning: Rare tumor causing blood pressure lability, weight loss; might also affect glucose metabolism.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause weight loss and lymphadenitis. Might also lead to hyperglycemia due to stress or infection.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: Can present with lymphadenitis, weight loss. May lead to hyperglycemia due to infection or medications.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Less common, but can cause constipation and blood pressure lability. Associated weight loss and potential disturbances in glucose metabolism could also be observed.

diagnoses.name: Hearing loss
diagnoses.details: There are many causes for hearing loss, including genetic, age-related, exposure to loud noises, infections, and certain systemic diseases.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.details: Angioedema is often associated with an allergic reaction, causing swelling beneath the skin. It can be hereditary or acquired.

diagnoses.name: Angiomata
diagnoses.details: Angiomata, plural for angiomatous lesions or hemangiomas, are benign vascular tumors. These can be isolated findings or part of systemic diseases like von Hippel-Lindau disease or Sturge-Weber syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia has many causes including iron-deficiency, chronic disease, autoimmune diseases, and genetic conditions like sickle cell.

diagnoses.name: Lymphadenopathy
diagnoses.details: Lymphadenopathy, or swollen lymph nodes, can result from infections, autoimmune diseases, or malignancies like lymphoma or leukemia.

diagnoses.name: Von Hippel-Lindau Disease
diagnoses.details: This is a hereditary condition characterized by the formation of tumors and fluid-filled sacs (cysts) in many different parts of the body. It can present with hemangioblastomas, which could manifest as angiomata, and can be associated with hearing loss due to endolymphatic sac tumors.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disease that affects multiple organ systems, SLE can cause anemia, lymphadenopathy, and, in rare cases, hearing loss. Angioedema is also a possible manifestation.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.details: A type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow, which can cause anemia and lymphadenopathy. Hearing loss is possible, particularly as a side effect of treatments or due to leukemic infiltration of the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma
diagnoses.details: This form of lymphoma can cause lymphadenopathy and, in advanced cases, can lead to anemia. It might indirectly cause hearing loss through obstruction of ear-related structures or as a side-effect of treatment.

diagnoses.name: Sickle Cell Disease
diagnoses.details: A genetic blood disorder causing misshapen red blood cells, leading to anemia and potentially lymphadenopathy. It can also cause hearing loss, often due to frequent infections or other complications.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV/AIDS can lead to a weakened immune system, making the body more susceptible to infections. It can also cause oral health issues such as leukoplakia. Psychiatric disorders including depression are common in people living with HIV/AIDS.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder that affects the immune system, leading to increased susceptibility to infections. Patients can also experience behavioral changes and emotional disorders.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) can lead to hypersensitivity reactions, increased susceptibility to infections due to compromised immune function, and psychiatric symptoms such as depression.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: MS can lead to cognitive impairments resembling attention deficits, depression, and a weakened immune response that increases susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Recurrent Aphthous Stomatitis
diagnoses.description: Commonly presenting as leukoplakia-like lesions, this condition can be associated with systemic symptoms like depression due to chronic pain and discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. Can present with leukoplakia due to leukemic infiltration and a compromised immune system, leading to increased susceptibility to infections. Patients may also experience depression.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body. Can present with oral ulcers similar to leukoplakia, depression, and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: Can cause oral changes mimicking leukoplakia, depressive symptoms due to decreased oxygen supply in the brain, and increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Can lead to neurological changes such as depression and cognitive deficits (similar to attention deficit symptoms), as well as increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A condition with potential to cause leukoplakia-like lesions in the mouth, psychological issues including depression, and has been associated with hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin C Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Vitamin C deficiency can lead to symptoms such as easy bleeding, malabsorption, and possibly irritated eyes due to its role in skin, vessel, and tissue health.

diagnoses.name: Coeliac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing symptoms like malabsorption and chronic back pain.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder causing chronic inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, which can cause symptoms like malabsorption and chronic pain including back discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue, chronic pain, including backaches, and can accompany malabsorption issues in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain, fatigue, and areas of tenderness, might also be related to malabsorption syndromes.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal increase of white blood cells. Symptoms can include easy bleeding and bruising.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs, manifesting symptoms such as hyperthermia and malabsorption.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth. It can sometimes lead to systemic issues such as hyperthermia and chronic pain.

diagnoses.name: Hemophilia
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your blood doesn't clot normally because it lacks sufficient blood-clotting proteins. This can lead to easy bleeding even with minor injuries.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to symptoms like irritated eyes, mouth sores, skin rashes, and systemic symptoms like fever (hyperthermia).

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines are a type of headache that can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine with aura involves visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear before the headache, including speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, speech or language difficulties, muscle weakness on one side of the body, and others, depending on the tumor’s location.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including muscle weakness, difficulty speaking (dysarthria), and neurological impairments like aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA doesn’t cause permanent damage. Symptoms include weakness, difficulty speaking, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain caused by a viral infection. It can cause flu-like symptoms, including a headache, fever, and weakness, as well as severe symptoms such as seizures, problems with movement or sensation, and speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include headache, fever, neck stiffness, confusion, and phonophobia. Severe disease can lead to neurological complications, including weakness and problems with speech.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus, immune cells, and other material in the brain, usually from a bacterial or fungal infection. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, speech difficulties, and neurological problems.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A subarachnoid hemorrhage is bleeding into the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain. This condition often presents with a sudden, severe headache along with other symptoms such as difficulty speaking, phonophobia, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barré Syndrome is a rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves. Weakness and tingling in the extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing the whole body. Speech difficulties can also occur in some cases.
